definition.value: A ketimine, R2C=NR' (R =/= H), in which R' is a keto (C=O) group.
A sulfonic acid containing the camphorsulfonate anion.
A ketone containing a hydroxy group on the beta-carbon relative to the C=O group.
A beta-hydroxy ketone formed by hydroxylation of 4-methylpentan-2-one at the 4-position. It has been isolated from Achnatherum robustum.
Any salt or ester of camphorsulfonic acid.

A carbamate ester that is terbutaline in which both of the phenolic hydroxy groups have been protected as the corresponding N,N-dimethylcarbamates. A long acting beta-adrenoceptor agonist used in the treatment of asthma, it is a prodrug for terbutaline.
The conjugate base of camphorsulfonic acid.
A polyketide compound synthesized from two ketide units. Diketides are derivatives of a 4-carbon skeleton.
The salt formed from the acetylide monoanion and a single sodium cation.
The salt formed from the acetylide dianion and two sodium cations.
The monoanion formed by loss of one proton from acetylene (ethyne).
A piperazine-2-carboxamide having (S)-configuration.
A piperazine-2-carboxylic acid having (S)-configuration.
An alpha-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of piperazine-2-carboxylic acid.
A phosphocholine that is the 4-nitrophenyl ester of choline phosphate.
The monodehydrogenated form of phosphocholine; the inorganic hapten formed from phosphocholine in hapten-protein conjugates.
A ketoaldohexose compound consisting of a pyranose ring with a keto group at the 2-position.
A 2-deoxyribose phosphate bearing a triphosphate substituent at an unspecified position.
An N-acyl-amino acid where the acyl component is an L-aminoacyl group with the amino acid component also having L-configuration.
A ketoaldohexose compound consisting of a pyranose ring with a keto group at the 3-position.
The R enantiomer of camphorsulfonic acid.
The 3-dehydro derivative of D-glucose.
The S enantiomer of camphorsulfonic acid.
A D-galactosamine 1-phosphate compound having an N-acetyl substituent.
The beta-anomer of N-acetyl-D-galactosamine 1-phosphate.
A disaccharide compound comprising a D-apiofuranosyl residue joined to D-glucopyranose via a beta-1,6-linkage.
The R enantiomer of camphorsulfonate.
The S enantiomer of camphorsulfonate.
The monoimine of 1,2-benzoquinone.
An anthocyanidin glucoside having a 6-O-malonylglucosyl residue at the 3-position attached via a beta-linkage.
A primary amide formed between lactobionic acid and hexane-1,6-diamine.
The L-enantiomer of N-acylhomoserine.
The sulfate salt of 4-methylaminophenol.
An N-acyl-amino acid consisting of homoserine bearing an unspecified N-acyl substituent.
The D-enantiomer of N-acylhomoserine.
The phenol that is the N-methyl derivative of 4-aminophenol.
Compounds containing a cyclic dicarboximide skeleton in which the two carboacyl groups on nitrogen together with the nitrogen itself form a 1H-pyrrole-2,5-dione structure.
Any guanosine containing a nitro group.
Guanosine substituted at the purine 8-position by a nitro group.

A tetracyclic diterpenoid that is grayanotoxane in which the pro-R hydrogen at position 14 is substituted by an acetoxy group and in which the 3beta-, 5-, 6beta-, 10-, and 16- positions are substituted by hydroxy groups.
Guanosine substituted at the ribosyl 5'-position by a nitro group.

An N-acetyl-beta-D-glycosaminyl glycopeptide consisting of an N-acetyl-beta-D-glycosaminyl-(1->4)-N-acetylmuramoyl moiety attached to the amino terminus of the pentapeptide L-Ala-gamma-D-Glu-L-Lys-D-Ala-D-Ala via an amide linkage.
Aldimines in which the the imino group is bonded to the methyl group of o-cresol or a derivative thereof.
Phenol with an iminomethyl substituent at the 2-position; the parent of the class of salicylaldehyde imines.
Salicylaldehyde imines with a tosyl (toluene-p-sulfonyl) group bonded to the imine N atom.
